# Why do rockets drift?

# Rockets drift primarily because they are pushed horizontally by lateral winds while suspended under a parachute. The parachute relies on massive aerodynamic drag to slow the descent, but this large surface area acts like a sail catching the moving air. The longer the rocket spends floating back to the ground, the further these wind currents will carry it away from the launch site.

# Why do launch operators monitor weather?

# Launch operators closely monitor the weather to ensure the structural integrity of the vehicle and the safety of the surrounding public. High-altitude shear winds can severely alter a rocket's upward flight path or cause dangerous mechanical stress during ascent. Tracking wind patterns also allows recovery teams to calculate precise drift zones, ensuring the descending hardware lands safely within designated boundaries rather than in populated areas.

# How might weather affect spacecraft landings?

# Weather directly threatens spacecraft landings by introducing unpredictable crosswinds that can push descending capsules miles away from their targeted recovery zones. Furthermore, poor visibility, high wind speeds, or rough ocean waves can dangerously delay rescue crews attempting to safely extract astronauts after splashdown. Mission control will routinely postpone a spacecraft's return from orbit if atmospheric conditions risk interfering with parachute deployment or the overall safety of the recovery operations.
